**Drought conditions expand in Lincoln and statewide, but relief could be on the way**
Drought conditions in Nebraska have worsened, with nearly 35% of the state now in at least a moderate drought, including nearly 9% in severe drought. In Lancaster County, the portion of the area in moderate drought more than doubled in one week, going from 37% to 76%, and the drought area now includes Lincoln. However, relief could be on the way as the National Weather Service is forecasting 2-3 inches of rain for Lincoln and many other parts of Southeast Nebraska from late Friday night into Monday morning. The weather service said, 'Our stretch of dry weather is nearing its end, rain will be nearly universal this weekend across eastern Nebraska and western Iowa.' The rain this weekend will also usher in much cooler temperatures, with Sunday's high forecast to only reach 63, followed by temperatures in the upper 60s to upper 70s Monday through Thursday.
